"'''The Ballad of Paladin'''" is a song written by [[Johnny Western]], [[Richard Boone]], and [[Sam Rolfe]] and performed by [[Duane Eddy]]. The song reached #10 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and #33 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1962.<ref>[http://www.musicvf.com/song.php?title=The+Ballad+of+Paladin+by+Duane+Eddy&id=13115 Duane Eddy, "The Ballad of Paladin" Chart Positions] Retrieved April 28, 2014</ref> Members of the [[Western Writers of America]] chose it as one of the Top 100 Western songs of all time.<ref name="Top100">{{Cite web|title=The Top 100 Western Songs|author=Western Writers of America|year=2010|authorlink=Western Writers of America|publisher=American Cowboy|url=http://www.americancowboy.com/culture/top-100-western-songs|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RjFQXqGy?url=http://www.americancowboy.com/culture/top-100-western-songs|archivedate=10 August 2014|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> Eddy's flip side was the theme to ''[[The Wild Westerners]]''.

The song was produced by [[Lee Hazlewood]] and arranged by [[Bob Thompson (musician)|Bob Thompson]].<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/478047 Duane Eddy, "The Ballad of Paladin" single release] Retrieved April 28, 2014</ref>  Drummer [[Earl Palmer]] played on the session.<ref>Scherman, Tony, Backbeat: The Earl Palmer Story, forward by Wynton Marsalis, Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington D.C., 1999 p. 176</ref>

It was used heavily in the film ''[[Stand by Me (film)|Stand by Me]]''.

==Other versions==
*[[Johnny Western]] recorded a version that was the theme to the television show ''[[Have Gun â€“ Will Travel]]''. Years later, he recorded a parody, "The Ballad of Palindrome", with the [[western swing]] and comedy group [[Riders in the Sky (band)|Riders in the Sky]].
*[[Al Caiola]] released a version as part of an [[Extended play|EP]] in [[1962 in music|1962]].<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/uax1503 Al Caiola, "The Ballad of Paladin" EP release] Retrieved April 28, 2014</ref>
*[[Faron Young]] released a version as part of an [[Extended play|EP]] in [[1963 in music|1963]].<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/dj122 Faron Young, "The Ballad of Paladin" EP release] Retrieved April 28, 2014</ref>

